# 6. あの日の写真は

Kohane: (Okay, we still haven't tried... Oh, we could try a low-angle shot.)
Kohane: Aoyagi, I'd like to try a low-angle shot next. Can you try looking down at the camera for me?
Toya: Okay.
Kohane: (Hmm... This isn't bad, but...)
Toya: How'd that turn out, Azusawa?
Kohane: So, it looks great... And you look cool and mature...
Kohane: But because of how our second photo went, I think we're going to have to find a way to do better...
Haruka: Yeah, we may need to try something completely different...
Haruka: For example, we could try for more charm like Airi and the others. Something that really catches people's attention.
Kohane: Charm...?
Kohane: Now that you mention it, I've been trying to take eye-catching photos, but haven't really been thinking about the whole picture like they have...
Kohane: Then, what if we tried using some props like them? But I don't have any good ideas from the top of my head...
Haruka: Why don't we take a quick break? Some ideas might come to us after we've had a chance to rest a little...
Kohane: Oh, good idea... Thanks for the suggestion, Haruka.
Toya: Then, I'm going to go get something to drink.
Haruka: I'll go with you. Would you like anything, Kohane?
Kohane: No, I'm okay. You two go without me.
Kohane: (But how do you achieve that sort of charm? I need to think of a way...)
Kohane: (No, I won't be able to beat Ena and the others at their own game.)
Kohane: (Still, are we really going to be able to take something better by trying whatever comes to mind like this...?)
Kohane: I'm supposed to be taking a break, but my mind wants to keep trying to think of something...
???: <Heya, Kohane!>
Kohane: Huh?
Kohane: Luka! KAITO!
Luka: <Sorry for dropping in so suddenly. We came to visit since you said you'd be doing your shoot for that photo contest today!>
KAITO: <So, how are things going? Is something bothering you by chance...?>
Kohane: Actually, yes... We've been able to take a couple of good photos, but we're having trouble getting back into the top ten...
Kohane: I want to take something better, but I'm not really sure what to do.
Luka: <Something better...?>
Luka: <First, can you show us what you've already taken? We might be able to help you after we've had a chance to look!>
Kohane: Oh, sure...! Any advice would be really helpful right now...!
Kohane: So, here's what we've taken so far...
Luka: <Wow! Toya looks so cool!>
KAITO: <What a beautiful shot! I really like how the light's hitting him.>
KAITO: <Hmm... I honestly only have good things to say about this.>
Luka: <Me too!>
Luka: <But you want to take an even better one, right, Kohane?>
Luka: <Actually... In your mind, what makes a photo “good”?>
Kohane: Huh?
Luka: <If you clarified that, then we might be able to figure out the solution to this problem!>
Kohane: Uhh...
Kohane: To me, a good photo is...
Kohane: (That's really hard to put into words...)
Kohane: (I try to copy the way other people frame things and use lighting, but that alone doesn't guarantee quality...)
Kohane: (There are plenty of great photos out there that don't adhere to basic foundations.)
Kohane: (So, what is it that makes a photo “good”...?)
Kohane: ...
Luka: <I'm sorry, Kohane! It wasn't meant to be such a hard question!>
Kohane: No, I'm sorry for not being able to find the right words...
KAITO: <That's understandable. If someone asked me what makes a song “good”, I probably wouldn't be able to give a quick response either.>
Luka: <I know...! Kohane, can you tell us about some of the times when you thought you took some really good pictures?>
Kohane: When I...? Uhh...
Kohane: Oh...
Kohane: I think the photos I took of a show I saw at PXL are the first ones that I thought were really good...
Luka: <PXL? You mean that amusement park you really love?>
Kohane: Yes!
Kohane: I was in junior high school and it was the first time I took a photo using the camera my dad gave me...
Kohane: The show was so magical. I got so excited that I couldn't help but take so many photos.
Kohane: Most of them didn't turn out great. They were blurry and poorly framed...
Kohane: But I liked what I took... I still feel that way even when I look at them now.
Luka: <Oh? Why's that?>
Kohane: Why...?
Kohane: I don't really know why... But I get really excited whenever I look at them.
Kohane: Seeing the cast members' bright smiles and the sparkling lights puts me right back in that moment.
KAITO: <I see... Then, it sounds like those photos mean quite a lot to you.>
Kohane: Oh, yes... They really do.
Luka: <But I feel like all the pictures you take are beautiful and compelling... I always get excited whenever I look at them...>
Kohane: Wait, you do...?
Luka: <Yes! I remember one of those flowers that looked so pretty in full bloom... Or that family of cats, which was so heartwarming...>
Luka: <It's clear what you were feeling each time you went to capture a scene.>
Luka: <Which is why I really love your work, Kohane. I think all the pictures you take are good.>
Kohane: Luka...
Kohane: (She understands what my photos are really about. That makes me so happy...)
Kohane: (Oh...)
Kohane: (So, all my photos... I guess they're a record of what I felt after seeing those things...)
Kohane: (Which allows me to go back in time, relive them and even share them with others... Is that why I love photography so much?)
Kohane: So, to me, a “good” photo is...
Kohane: Thank you... I think I know how to answer your question now.
KAITO: <Oh, really?>
Kohane: Yes... I want to leave a record of the things that really move my heart.
Kohane: And take photos in a way that others can understand what I was feeling. That's my aim...
Kohane: But I'm not really sure if that's the best way to receive likes from others...
KAITO: <Who cares? You should take the photos you want, Kohane!>
Luka: <What he said! Because if you don't think what you took is good, then there's no way others will!>
KAITO: <However, based on that logic, Kohane, you'll need to take a picture of Toya that you personally like...>
Luka: <Hmm... What does that entail?>
Kohane: Oh...
Luka: <Oh, was that a lightbulb?>
Kohane: Umm.... What if we took one of him smiling?
KAITO: <Smiling?>
Kohane: Yes. When we first formed our team, Aoyagi's facial expressions didn't really change much.
Kohane: But as we spent more time together, he slowly began to learn how to smile and laugh...
Kohane: Which sort of felt like evidence that we'd become close enough that he's willing to open up to us. I remember how happy I was after realizing that.
Kohane: So, if we can somehow recreate that heartwarming atmosphere, then I think everyone who sees it will really like it...
Luka: <Yeah, that's a wonderful idea!>
Luka: <Then, for your last attempt, you'll be going for Toya's smile...?>
Kohane: Yes...!
Kohane: I genuinely believe that a photo of him smiling will end up being the best one we take today!
